The Americas
------------
[1] USA (Nebraska)
Date: Sat 2 Aug 2014
Source: Star Herald [summ., edited]
http://www.starherald.com/news/local_news/measles-in-nebraska-for-first-time-since/article_279245e5-834a-5a30-9f92-f1ed70794999.html


In 2000, the government declared measles was eliminated in the United States due to its successful vaccination program. Shortly after that, the number of cases increased. "Nebraska had its 1st confirmed case of measles last week in Eastern Nebraska," said Sandy Preston, immunization clinic coordinator for Community Health in Scotts Bluff County. "Because vaccines are so safe and effective, we haven't had a case since 1990." Preston said people choose to not immunize due to fear or incorrect science, but numerous studies have found no connection between autism and vaccines. "One doctor conducted an improper study and had his paper retracted from Lancet, but he had enough influence that people listen to him," Preston said. "He lost his license, but meanwhile 8 children died." Infectious diseases that once regularly killed or harmed infants, children, and adults have been reduced or eliminated with vaccines. "We've had such a leg up people have forgotten how devastating it is," she said. "There are young people and doctors who've never seen these diseases."

According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), vaccines contain the same antigens or parts of antigens that cause diseases, but antigens in vaccines are either killed or greatly weakened. Antigens do not cause disease. They make the immune system produce antibodies against them. Through vaccination, children develop immunity without suffering from the actual diseases. No vaccine is 100 percent effective. Immunization also helps those who cannot get a vaccine because they are too young, cannot produce antibodies or other medical reasons. The herd immunity helps prevent it from spreading. Adults can also get measles if they are not vaccinated. Children under 5 and adults over 20 are at higher risk for measles complications including pneumonia, and a higher risk of hospitalization and death from measles than school-aged children and adolescents. About one out of 10 children with measles also gets an ear infection, and up to one out of 20 gets pneumonia, CDC said. For every 1000 children who get measles, one or 2 will die. "Of the fatalities we see, it's usually associated with pneumonia and encephalitis," Preston said.

August is National Immunization Awareness Month (NIAM), which increases awareness about immunizations across the lifespan. Community Health has several programs for those who can and cannot afford immunisations. "Vaccines are one of the safest methods to protect you and your child," Preston said. "Please have your children protected."

[Byline: Irene North]

